<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900918-0068</DOCNO><DOCID>900918-0068.</DOCID><HL>   Former Amex Systems   Chief Pleads Guilty   To Bribery Charges</HL><DATE>09/18/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   ALEXANDRIA, Va. -- The former chief executive officer of aLos Angeles defense contractor pleaded guilty to bribing Navyofficials for their assistance in obtaining militarycontracts, federal prosecutors said.   Manuel Caldera, former chairman, chief executive andprincipal stockholder of Amex Systems Inc., waived indictmentand pleaded guilty in federal court here to paying thousandsof dollars to two Navy engineers for their help in obtainingand maintaining contracts to build transit receivers for Navyships, according to U.S. Attorney Henry Hudson. The guiltyplea arose out of the government's continuing investigationof defense procurement fraud, known as Operation Illwind.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Caldera made the illegal payments in connection withsix Navy contracts awarded to his company between 1978 and1984, according to his plea agreement. The contracts had avalue of roughly $40 million, with potential follow-on valueof an additional $100 million between 1984 and 1988, Mr.Hudson said in a statement. Mr. Caldera sold Amex Systems toAllied-Signal Inc. of Morristown, N.J., in November 1984 for$45 million, the prosecutor said.   Mr. Caldera, 59 years old, couldn't be reached forcomment. He faces a maximum sentence of seven years inprison.   A spokesman for Allied-Signal said the company sold AmexSystems to Science Applications International of San Diego in1988.   A senior official at Science Applications said AmexSystems was merged into its operations shortly after thepurchase. The official said Mr. Caldera &quot;was not part of theoperation when we acquired it.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>